<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-334-034  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 334 034.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Design andamp; Test of Computers  June 1989 v6 n3 p58(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A built-in test module for fault isolation. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vasanthavada, Nagesh; Kanopoulos, Nick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A board-level implementation of built-in testing-switch modulesfor isolating faulty chips is presented.andP;  The testing-switchmodule is incorporated into a board design by first partitioningthe chips into ambiguity groups (AGs) and then introducing theswitches so that all AG inputs pass through them.andP;  A test-controlunit performs preliminary tests on the switch modules themselves.andO;In the actual fault-isolation test, the testing switch method isfaster than logic-block circuit schemes.andP;  It is not a substitutefor self-test and chip-level boundary scan, but is lest costly andcan be used in situations where boundary scan is impractical forall chips on a board.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fault ToleranceDiagnosticsCircuit DesignBoards-CardsEfficiencyArchitecture.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Architecture of the testing-switch module (chart)An example of simultaneously testable ambiguity groups (chart)Incorporating testing-switch modules in the digital-filter boarddesign (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>